<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="UTF-8" />
		<title>Technical Documentation Page</title>
		<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css" />
	</head>

	<body>
		<nav id="navbar">
			<header>
				<h1>Coding Log</h1>
			</header>
			<a class="nav-link" href="#Introduction">Introduction</a>
			<a class="nav-link" href="#Installation">Installation</a>
			<a class="nav-link" href="#Creating_logs">Creating logs</a>
			<a class="nav-link" href="#Adapting_the_program">Adapting the program</a>
			<a class="nav-link" href="#Future_functionality">Future functionality</a>
		</nav>
		<main id="main-doc">
			<section class="main-section" id="Introduction">
				<header>
					<h2>Introduction</h2>
				</header>
				<p>
					This program can be used to create a log for coding activities done
					daily or any other cadence you choose. The program asks the user a set
					of questions about what they've done related to coding, what questions
					or issues have come up, and next steps. It then writes the questions
					and answers to a markdown file in a location of the user's choosing.
				</p>

				<h3>Purpose</h3>
				<p>
					I created this program as a project while learning backend development
					with boot.dev. Mostly I did it for the sake of learning how to create
					a first project (ever!) but also wanted something that I would use
					myself.
				</p>
				<p>
					The purpose of this program is to make it easy to keep quick logs of
					coding activity so that one can keep track of progress. This is
					particularly useful when working on projects, to kepe track of
					questions/issues and answers, and next steps to work on.
				</p>

				<h3>Functionality</h3>
				<p>
					This coding log program runs in the command line interface (CLI), or
					terminal. In future, I plan to create a graphical user interface (GUI)
					to make the log entry inputs look and feel a bit cleaner than they do
					in the terminal interface.
				</p>
				<p>
					It provides a set of questions to the user, and then writes the
					questions and answers to a markdown file at the file path of the
					user's choosing. More specifically, the program:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						Creates a markdown file with the current month if none exists
						already, giving it the title "YYYY-mm", and putting into a filepath
						the user enters.
					</li>
					<ul>
						<li>
							If a file for the current month exists already, it writes to that
							existing file.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<li>
						The programs writes the questions and the user-supplied answers
						under a header with the current date on that file.
						<ul>
							<li>
								If a hearder with the current date already exists, it writes a
								new section under a subheader with "Updated at" and the current
								time of writing in the user's timezone.
							</li>
						</ul>
					</li>

					<li>
						The user is able to skip questions or exit the entire program early
						(instructions are provided in the program on how to do these
						things), in which case only the questions with answers supplied
						before the program completes will be written to the markdown file.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<section class="main-section" id="Installation">
				<header>
					<h2>Installation</h2>
				</header>
				<p>
					This program runs entirely in python and has no other dependencies.
					For future development I will likely use
					<span class="inline-code">tkinter</span> for the GUI, but that is part
					of the python package and doesn't require separate installation.
				</p>
				<p>To install and set up:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>
						Ensure you have python3 installed, with version 3.14 or higher
					</li>
					<li>Clone the program repository</li>
					<li>
						Run the <span class="inline-code">main.py</span> file to start the
						program; you can do this in the terminal or in an IDE that has an
						integrated terminal
					</li>
				</ol>
				<p>
					You can run the program (in the terminal or IDE, as discussed above)
					with the following command from within the directory where the program
					is located:
				</p>
				<code>python3 main.py</code>
				<p>
					If you use <span class="inline-code">uv</span> to manage your
					projects, you can use:
				</p>
				<code>uv run main.py</code><br />
			</section>

			<section class="main-section" id="Creating_logs">
				<header>
					<h2>Creating logs</h2>
				</header>
				<p>When you run the program, the following things will happen:</p>
				<p>
					<b>First</b>: You will need to enter a filepath for where the
					questions and answers will be saved. If this is not a valid filepath
					(or you don't enter anything) you will have two more chances to enter
					a valid filepath. Otherwise, the program will end.
				</p>

				<p>
					For example, you could enter the following to save the file in a
					Documents folder on a Mac:
				</p>
				<code>/Users/username/Documents/coding/logs</code>

				<p>
					<b>Second</b>: Once you enter a valid file path, a confirmation will
					be provided that the file will be saved to that path. A markdown file
					with the current month will be opened at that path. Then, basic
					instructions will appear for making the log (including how to skip
					questions or end early).
				</p>

				<p>
					<b>Third</b>: Questions will appear one at a time, and once the user
					answers each question the next will appear. As noted above, users can
					skip questions or end the whole program early if they choose, and if
					so, only the questions for which answers have been provided, along
					with the answers themselves, will be written to the markdown file.
				</p>

				<p>
					<b>Fourth</b>: If the user answers one or more questions, they are
					written to the markdown file already opened at the path defined by the
					user, and a confirmation message to that effect is provided, with the
					full path to the file so the user can review where the file is
					located. For example:
				</p>

				<code
					>Your answers have been saved in a markdown file at
					/Users/username/Documents/coding/logs/2026-06.md</code
				>

				<p>
					<b>Note</b>: If the user ends the program early, no confirmation
					message appears, but the answers already supplied, if any, are written
					to the markdown file.
				</p>
				<p></p>
			</section>

			<section class="main-section" id="Adapting_the_program">
				<header>
					<h2>Adapting the program</h2>
				</header>
				<p>
					The program has an <span class="inline-code">inputs.py</span> file
					that holds a list of questions as well as messages printed to the
					console. These can easily be changed as desired and the changes will
					propagate to <span class="inline-code">main.py</span>.
				</p>

				<p>
					For example, here are sample questions in the
					<span class="inline-code">inputs.py</span> file, that can be adapted
					if desired:
				</p>
				<code>
					q1 = "What are you working on?"<br />
					q2 = "What have you completed or accomplished?"<br />
					q3 = "Any questions or challenges coming up?"<br />
					q4 = "What are your next steps?"<br />
				</code>
				<p>
					You could adapt this program for any note-taking purpose, not just a
					coding log, by changing the questions asked.
				</p>
				<p>
					It could be possible also to provide different sets of questions for
					different purposes, and have the user provide an input saying which
					type of log they're writing, and the program would use that to choose
					the correspondign list of questions. This functionality is not
					provided in the current program, but is one way it could be adapted.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="main-section" id="Future_functionality">
				<header>
					<h2>Future functionality</h2>
				</header>
				<p>
					As noted above, I plan to use
					<span class="inline-code">tkinter</span> to generate a graphical user
					interface for asking and answering questions, largely to learn how to
					use that functionality. The program would still run in the terminal
					interface to begin (you'd need to start it there) but then it would
					open a GUI window for the questions and answers. Getting this to work
					may take some time, as I am starting with zero knowledge of how to do
					it.
				</p>
				<p>
					A stretch goal is to be able to tie the logs generated through this
					program to a static website, so that if the user chooses, the markdown
					file could be translated to html to be added to a static website. I
					have already developed a static website generator in python through a
					tutorial on boot.dev that takes markdown inputs and translates them to
					html, and at some point it would be interesting to be able to connect
					this kind of program to that kind of one. This may be far into the
					future though!
				</p>
			</section>
		</main>
	</body>
</html>
